c6S7jEtNw6II0PxPrN-VoKgjF_ygChfEVDJSlO0b3MFDYQeDm8IqHrhavs7u5uYD8lHkOF_p3Qu=
83maXW8f-vTLTmmvwx_qu4ZXP_QzlsEHgXZjiBXX5wPDPc2Z5qk6l5UaLEqxtHRPKBtFdLk3PIg=
Ex6gjffJbD2VeIpMeRBtJUKOYKnMUwTSkHa3Q ) :

If there is a single phrase that describes the effect of the Internet, it i=
s the elimination of friction. With the loss of friction, there is necessar=
ily the loss of everything built on friction, including value, privacy, and=
 livelihoods. And that=E2=80=99s only three examples! The Internet is pulli=
ng out the foundations of nearly every institution and social more that our=
 society is built upon.

Count me with those who believe the Internet is on par with the industrial =
revolution, the full impact of which stretched over centuries. And it wasn=
=E2=80=99t all good. Like today, the industrial revolution included a perio=
d of time that saw many lose their jobs and a massive surge in inequality. =
It also lifted millions of others out of sustenance farming. Then again, it=
 also propagated slavery, particularly in North America. The industrial rev=
olution led to new monetary systems, and it created robber barons. Modern d=
emocracies sprouted from the industrial revolution, and so did fascism and =
communism. The quality of life of millions and millions was unimaginably im=
proved, and millions and millions died in two unimaginably terrible wars.

Change is guaranteed, but the type of change is not; never is that more tru=
e than today. See, friction makes everything harder, both the good we can d=
o, but also the unimaginably terrible. In our zeal to reduce friction and o=
ur eagerness to celebrate the good, we ought not lose sight of the potentia=
l bad. We are creating the future, and =E2=80=9Cbetter=E2=80=9D does not wi=
n by default.

Set aside the dramatic centuries-spanning exposition; the fundamental point=
 is that the removal of friction leads to a different set of trade-offs. In=
 the case of targeting and tracking, the payoff is a massive increase in co=
nsumer welfare by virtue of access to all of the world=E2=80=99s informatio=
n (Google), and all of the world=E2=80=99s people (Meta); in the case of th=
ings like dark patterns and personal appeals, the payoff is ordering sungla=
sses for your upcoming fishing trip at 10am and having them in hand at 4pm,=
 or, more broadly, to have access to anything you need no matter where you =
live.

To note these trade-offs is not to say that the trade-off is worth it or no=
t; it=E2=80=99s to note that the trade-offs exist. And, to that end, the fr=
ustration so many feel about the FTC=E2=80=99s recent actions, particularly=
 this specific lawsuit, is the extent to which the Commission seems determi=
ned to act as if trade-offs don=E2=80=99t exist.

This is, of course, downstream from Chairperson Lina Khan=E2=80=99s famous =
law review article, Amazon=E2=80=99s Antitrust Paradox ( https://www.yalela=
wjournal.org/pdf/e.710.Khan.805_zuvfyyeh.pdf ). Khan, and much of the movem=
ent she represents, is intrinsically opposed to =E2=80=9Cbig=E2=80=9D, and =
frankly, I=E2=80=99m sympathetic to the point. The problem with this moveme=
nt=E2=80=99s critique, though, is that because it believes =E2=80=9Cbig is =
bad=E2=80=9D, it assumes that company=E2=80=99s become big by acting badly.

The reality of Aggregation Theory ( https://stratechery.com/2015/aggregatio=
n-theory/?access_token=3DeyJhbGciOiJSUzI1NiIsImtpZCI6InN0cmF0ZWNoZXJ5LnBhc3=
